3) Range:
Step 1: Introduce Range
Range may be defined as the difference between the highest and lowest
measurements in a group of data. Let Xmax be the largest or highest value and Xmin
be the smallest or lowest value. It is denoted by R and computed as follows:
R=Xmax−Xmin
Step 2: Relative Measure of Range
The relative measure of range is also known as coefficient of range or coefficient of
dispersion based on range which is calculated as follows:
Coefficient of range =Xmax−Xmin / Xmax+Xmin [Look in the book to get the equation]

5) The second last and last one should be Mean Deviation and Standard Deviation so, Write about the
difference between them:
Though mean deviation and standard deviation are the measures of dispersion including
all the items, they differ in following cases;
a. Deviations are taken from mean, median or both in case of mean deviation
whereas the deviations are taken only from the mean in case of standard
deviation.
b. Whether the deviation is positive or negative, only positive value is considered in
case of mean deviation but no such problem occurs in standard deviation.
c. Standard deviation follows different properties but mean deviation does not.

FOURTH VIDEO – Skewness
STEP 1: Give the introduction to Skewness.
Skewness is a lack of symmetry. It gives the degree of departure from the
symmetry. Measure of Skewness is a s descriptive statistical measure used to
measure the shape of the curve drawn from the frequency distribution or to
measure the direction of variation.
STEP 2: Types of Skewness.
1) No Skewness (or Symmetrical):
A distribution of data is said to have no skewness if the cure drawn from
the data is neither elongated more to the left side nor to the right side. The
curve, in this case, is equally elongated to the right as well as to the left.
For symmetrical distribution,
Mean=Median=Mode
2) Positive Skewness:
A distribution is said to have positive skewness or right skewed if the
curve drawn from the frequency distribution is more elongated to the right
side.
For positively skewed distribution,
Mean>Median>Mode
3) Negative Skewness:
A distribution is said to have negative skewness or left skewed if the curve
drawn from the frequency distribution is more elongated to the left side.
For negatively skewed distribution,
Mean<Median<Mode

STEP 4: DEFINE SAMPLE SPACE:
Any trial results in an outcome that corresponds to one and only one element of
the set S is called the sample space of the experiment and the elements are called
sample points. Sample space is generally denoted by S
Example: Write the sample space in two tosses of a coin.
Solution: Let H denote a head and T denote a tail in the experiment of
tossing of a coin.
S = {(H, H), (H, T), (T, H), (T, T)}.
Good to know: If two coins are tossed simultaneously then the sample
space S can be written as S = {H, H T, T H, T T}.
